{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01E9aMFXar9zmQgq5HwtVQ8i","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Good. The RabbitMQ Prometheus plugin doesn't expose a `rabbitmq_up` metric natively. The requirement says \"query rabbitmq_up returns 3 samples\". \n\nI need to create a `rabbitmq_up` metric. I can do this using Prometheus recording rules. I can add a recording rule to the Prometheus config that creates `rabbitmq_up` from `up{job=\"rabbitmq\"}`:\n\n```yaml\nrule_files:\n  - /etc/prometheus/rules/*.yml\n```\n\nWriting recording rules...\n\nI could create a separate ConfigMap for the rules and mount it in the Prometheus deployment, though that would trigger a pod restart.\n\nActually, the simpler approach is to add a `rules.yml` key to the existing `prometheus-config` ConfigMap and update the Prometheus config to reference it via `rule_files`. Since ConfigMap keys become files when mounted at `/etc/prometheus/`, I can just add the recording rules there and point to them in the main config.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":610,"cache_read_input_tokens":34740,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":610},"output_tokens":34,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"0d7fb30b-a2c8-49f2-85cf-4bf3df82e4d4","uuid":"9ef7966d-d007-4b98-b8a2-92addf7e15b1","request_id":"req_011Ccb1nm1W6wVUwpHWtNqZL"}
